Data Visualization Using Seaborn Package¶

Here we will see how to utilise python for analyising data.

Following Plots are created using seaborn package¶

  1. Distplot - Meant for showing Histogram and Kernel Density Estimation (Sum of all Gaussian Curves + RugPlots)

  2. Jointplot - Generates Histogram and Scatterplot together.

  3. Pairplot - Multiple Plots Together

  4. KDEPLOT - Kernel Density Estimation Plot

  5. Facet Grid Plots

Distplot¶

seaborn.distplot - Flexibly plot a univariate distribution of observations. This function combines the matplotlib hist function and plot the estimated PDF over the data. The calculation of bin size is automatic here.

The most convenient way to take a quick look at a univariate distribution in seaborn is the distplot() function. By default, this will draw a histogram and fit a kernel density estimate (KDE).

Bivariate plots - Cont Vs Cont¶

A bivariate plot is created using jointplots.

A pariplot is used to create scatterplot and histograms between the different numerical variables.

Bivariate plots - Categorical Variables¶

A Bivariate categorical var plot is created using stripplot.

Scatterplots¶

The most familiar way to visualize a bivariate distribution is a scatterplot, where each observation is shown with point at the x and y values.

You can draw a scatterplot with the matplotlib plt.scatter function, and it is also the default kind of plot shown by the jointplot() function:

sns.jointplot() - It generates scatterplot and histogram together

Jointplot¶

A joint plot shows the histogram and scatterplot together. These two can be shown separately as histogram and Tips

In [138]:
# Jointplot - Meant for Bivariate Distribution

# Syntax - sns.jointplot(x = , y = , data = ) # Generates Histogram and Scatterplot together.

sns.jointplot(x = "total_bill", y = "tip", data = tips, color="purple")
Out[138]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x1a3628d0f0>

Jointplot :: kind ="hex"¶

The bivariate analogue of a histogram is known as a hexbin plot, because it shows the counts of observations that fall within hexagonal bins. This plot works best with relatively large datasets. Also known as Hexbin Plots

In [111]:
# kind : { "scatter" | "reg" | "resid" | "kde" | "hex" }
sns.jointplot(x = "total_bill", y = "tip", data = tips, kind ="hex" ,color="lightcoral")

# certain points make it darker and lesser points make it lighter
# reg - scatterplot with regression line. The best line fit to the scatter point data
# kde = two dimensional KDE. Shows density where the points match up the most.
Out[111]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x1a2fabdc50>

Jointplot :: kind ="kde"¶

It is also possible to use the kernel density estimation to visualize a bivariate distribution. In seaborn, this kind of plot is shown with a contour plot and is available as a style in jointplot().

A Contour plot (sometimes called Level Plots) are a way to show a three-dimensional surface on a two-dimensional plane. It graphs two predictor variables X Y on the y-axis and a response variable Z as contours.

In [136]:
sns.jointplot(x = tips["total_bill"], y = tips["tip"],kind = "kde", color="purple") # contour plot
Out[136]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x1a35f99e10>

Pairplot¶

A Pairplot essentially plots pair wise relationship between variables. It supports color hue for cat columns. Takes Jointplot for numerical columns and puts it together.

In [129]:
# Pairplot of Tips
# syntax - sns.pairplot("dataframe")
# hue : string (variable name), optional :: Cat Column especially
sns.pairplot(tips, hue = "sex", palette="Set2")

# Inference - Diagonal is histogram being one variable. Rest It would show the Scatterplot.
# Hue is used to color the plot using categorical columns.

Grid Based Maps - PairGrid¶

Grid Based Maps give you the power to customize the maps. Lets put all the maps in one place in grid format. Here lower part of the Grid will be a jointmap kde, upper would be a scatterplot using plt.scatter Diagonal would be a distplot

g = sns.PairGrid(tips) g.map(plt.scatter, color="purple") # Ceating scatterplots of all the Num Variables

In [178]:
g = sns.PairGrid(tips)
g.map_diag(sns.distplot)
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot)
g.map_upper(plt.scatter)
Out[178]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x1a3d4639e8>
In [9]:
# iris dataset
iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
g = sns.PairGrid(iris)
g.map_diag(sns.distplot)
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot, color="purple")
g.map_upper(plt.scatter)
Out[9]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x1a19bb79b0>

Grid Based Maps - Facet Grid¶

Grid Based Maps give you the power to customize the maps. Lets put all the maps in one place in grid format. Here lower part of the Grid will be a jointmap kde, upper would be a scatterplot using plt.scatter Diagonal would be a distplot

In [7]:
# the syntax is same as Pairgrid
face = sns.FacetGrid(data=tips, row = "time", col = "smoker")
face.map(sns.distplot,"total_bill")
